# Ferroque

A production-minded background job queue service built in Rust. Ferroque lets any internal service offload slow or failure-prone work — sending emails, resizing images, syncing third-party APIs — to async workers that handle retries, scheduling, and failure recovery automatically.

Built with Axum, SQLx, Tokio, and PostgreSQL. No Redis. No external message broker. Just Postgres doing what it does best.

---

## Why this exists

Any backend that does real work eventually hits the same problem: some tasks are too slow or too unreliable to run inside an HTTP request. Ferroque solves this by acting as the infrastructure layer between *"something happened"* and *"the work got done"* — letting callers submit jobs and return immediately while workers handle execution in the background.

---

## Architecture

```
Caller service  ──POST /jobs──▶  HTTP API (Axum)
                                      │
                                      ▼
                               PostgreSQL (jobs table)
                                      │
                         ┌────────────┴────────────┐
                         ▼                         ▼
                   Worker pool               Scheduler
                  (Tokio tasks)           (stuck job reaper)
                         │
                         ▼
                   Job handler fn
```

**HTTP API** — Axum REST API protected by API key middleware. Accepts job submissions and exposes job status endpoints.

**PostgreSQL** — Single source of truth. Every job lives in a `jobs` table with a status that drives the full lifecycle. Using Postgres as the queue (rather than Redis) gives durability and transactional guarantees with one less infrastructure dependency.

**Worker pool** — A configurable number of concurrent Tokio tasks that poll for work. Workers claim jobs atomically using `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`, which prevents any two workers from picking up the same job without any application-level locking.

**Scheduler** — A background Tokio task that runs every 30 seconds to reap stuck jobs. If a worker crashes mid-execution, the scheduler detects jobs that have been in `running` state too long and requeues them.

---

## Job lifecycle

```
Pending ──▶ Running ──▶ Succeeded
                │
                ▼
             Failed ──▶ Pending  (retries remaining, exponential backoff)
                │
                ▼
              Dead  (max attempts reached)
```

Retry backoff is calculated entirely in SQL:

```sql
run_at = NOW() + (INTERVAL '1 second' * POWER(2, attempts))
```

Attempt 1 retries after 2s, attempt 2 after 4s, attempt 3 after 8s — no application-level timers.

---

## API

All endpoints require an `x-api-key` header.

### Enqueue a job

```
POST /jobs
```

```json
{
  "job_type": "send_email",
  "payload": { "to": "user@example.com" },
  "priority": 0,
  "max_attempts": 3,
  "run_at": "2026-04-01T09:00:00Z"
}
```

`run_at` defaults to now. Set it in the future for scheduled jobs. `priority` is used to order job pickup — higher values run first.

**Response `201 Created`:**

```json
{
  "id": "018e1b2c-3d4e-7f8a-9b0c-1d2e3f4a5b6c",
  "job_type": "send_email",
  "status": "pending",
  "run_at": "2026-04-01T09:00:00Z"
}
```

### Get a job

```
GET /jobs/:id
```

```json
{
  "id": "018e1b2c-3d4e-7f8a-9b0c-1d2e3f4a5b6c",
  "job_type": "send_email",
  "payload": { "to": "user@example.com" },
  "status": "succeeded",
  "attempts": 1,
  "max_attempts": 3,
  "error": null,
  "run_at": "2026-04-01T09:00:00Z",
  "created_at": "2026-03-23T08:00:00Z"
}
```

### List jobs

```
GET /jobs
```

Returns the 100 most recently created jobs.

### Cancel a job

```
POST /jobs/:id/cancel
```

Moves a `pending` job to `dead`. Has no effect on jobs already running or completed.

---

## Running locally

**Prerequisites:** Docker and Docker Compose.

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/ferroque
cd ferroque
docker compose up
```

The service starts on port `3000`. Default API key is `ferroque-secret-key`.

```bash
# Enqueue a job
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/jobs \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "x-api-key: ferroque-secret-key" \
  -d '{"job_type": "send_email", "payload": {"to": "user@example.com"}}'

# Check its status
curl http://localhost:3000/jobs/<id> \
  -H "x-api-key: ferroque-secret-key"
```

---

## Running without Docker

```bash
# Start Postgres
createdb ferroque

# Set environment
cp .env.example .env   # edit DATABASE_URL and API_KEY

# Run
cargo run
```

---

## Tests

```bash
# Unit tests (no database required)
cargo test --lib

# All tests including integration
cargo test
```

The test suite covers auth enforcement, job enqueue/retrieve round trips, error responses, the handler registry, and error-to-HTTP-status mapping.

---

## Key technical decisions

**Postgres as the queue.** Most job queue implementations reach for Redis. Ferroque uses Postgres deliberately — jobs are transactional data that benefit from durability and ACID guarantees. A crashed worker cannot cause a job to vanish. The tradeoff is throughput: Postgres tops out at tens of thousands of jobs per second where Redis can do millions. For most real-world workloads, that's not a constraint.

**`SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`.** This single Postgres feature makes the whole system safe at any concurrency. When a worker claims a job, it locks that row. Any other worker that runs the same query simultaneously sees the lock and skips to the next available job. No application-level mutexes, no distributed locks, no coordination overhead.

**Exponential backoff in SQL.** Retry delay is calculated at the database level using `POWER(2, attempts)` rather than in application code. This keeps retry logic consistent regardless of which worker processes a job and eliminates any in-memory state that could be lost on a crash.

**Tokio for concurrency.** Workers are async tasks, not OS threads. A pool of 4 workers consumes 4 Tokio tasks rather than 4 threads — the same process can handle hundreds of concurrent workers without the memory overhead of a thread-per-worker model.

---

## What I'd build next

- **`LISTEN/NOTIFY` instead of polling.** Currently workers poll Postgres every 500ms. Postgres's pub/sub mechanism would let the database wake workers instantly when a new job arrives, reducing latency and unnecessary queries.
- **Per-queue concurrency limits.** Right now all job types share the same worker pool. A dedicated queue per job type would let you say "max 2 concurrent email jobs, max 10 concurrent image resizes."
- **Web UI for job inspection.** A simple dashboard showing job counts by status, recent failures, and retry history — useful for operators debugging production issues.
- **Metrics endpoint.** Prometheus-compatible counters for jobs enqueued, succeeded, failed, and dead — plus worker utilisation and average queue depth.

---

## Stack

- **[Axum](https://github.com/tokio-rs/axum)** — async web framework
- **[SQLx](https://github.com/launchbadge/sqlx)** — async Postgres driver with compile-time query verification
- **[Tokio](https://tokio.rs)** — async runtime
- **[PostgreSQL 16](https://www.postgresql.org)** — job persistence and atomic claiming
- **[serde](https://serde.rs)** — serialization
- **[thiserror](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror)** — structured error types